There is already a right to privacy guaranteed in the California Constitution, but it is not explicitly defined. Voting YES on Prop 1 would change that, and it is critically important that we make sure it passes in November! #ReproductiveRights #Prop1

Proposition 1 changes the California Constitution to say that the state cannot deny or interfere with a person‚Äôs reproductive freedom and that people have the fundamental right to choose: 

- Whether or not to have an abortion 
- Whether or not to use contraceptives
I am asking you all as friends and supporters of reproductive choice to support that committee with a contribution. You can contribute here via ActBlue: https://t.co/UaajlKFyUv

As the father of a teenage daughter, I will always remember the fear and frustration that followed the leak of the Dobbs decision. That feeling, as much as anything else, is what drove me to form a committee to advocate on behalf of Proposition 1.

It's easy to pretend that we're invulnerable in California to the anti-choice politics that are infecting our Supreme Court and many state governments ‚Äì but, to paraphrase Dr. Martin Luther King, their injustice is a threat to our justice.

This November, Californians will vote on Proposition 1, a state constitutional amendment to protect abortion rights in our state. I am proud to have worked on this amendment with Governor Gavin Newsom, Senate Pro Tem Toni Atkins and Speaker Anthony Rendon.
